{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What Is Flow State?"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Every CrewAI Flow has a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "state",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " \u2014 a Pydantic model that all steps can read and write via "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "self.state",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". State is the single source of truth for a flow run: it is initialised before the first step, mutated by each step, and available in full after "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "flow.kickoff()",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " returns."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "CrewAI Flow State lifecycle diagram",
          "title": null
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Steps communicate in two ways: by returning values (which the listener receives as an argument) and by mutating "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "self.state",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " directly. Use return values for tight step-to-step data handoffs; use state for data that multiple downstream steps need to access."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Defining a Typed State"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Subclass Pydantic's "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "BaseModel",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and annotate every field with a type and default value. Then pass it as the generic parameter to "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Flow",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from pydantic import BaseModel, Field\nfrom typing import Optional, List\nfrom crewai.flow.flow import Flow, listen, start\n\nclass ResearchState(BaseModel):\n    # Input fields \u2014 set via kickoff(inputs={...})\n    topic: str = \"\"\n    audience: str = \"general\"\n\n    # Intermediate fields \u2014 written by steps during execution\n    outline: List[str] = Field(default_factory=list)\n    draft: str = \"\"\n    word_count: int = 0\n    review_passed: bool = False\n\n    # Output fields \u2014 populated by the final step\n    final_article: Optional[str] = None\n    error: Optional[str] = None\n\nclass ResearchFlow(Flow[ResearchState]):\n    pass   # steps defined below"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Use "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Field(default_factory=list)",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "code"
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " for mutable defaults like lists and dicts. Using "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "= []",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "code"
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " directly in a Pydantic model is safe (Pydantic handles it), but "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "default_factory",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "code"
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " is more explicit."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Populating State at Kickoff"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pass an "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "inputs",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " dict to "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "flow.kickoff()",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". CrewAI matches keys to state field names and sets them before the first step runs."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "flow = ResearchFlow()\nresult = flow.kickoff(inputs={\n    \"topic\": \"quantum error correction\",\n    \"audience\": \"software engineers\",\n})\n\n# Both fields are available in the first step:\n# self.state.topic    == \"quantum error correction\"\n# self.state.audience == \"software engineers\" "
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Fields not in "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "inputs",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " keep their model defaults. Unknown keys in "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "inputs",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " that don't match any state field are silently ignored."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Reading and Writing State in Steps"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "class ResearchFlow(Flow[ResearchState]):\n\n    @start()\n    def create_outline(self):\n        # Read state\n        topic = self.state.topic\n        audience = self.state.audience\n\n        # Write state\n        self.state.outline = [\n            f\"1. Introduction to {topic}\",\n            f\"2. Key concepts for {audience}\",\n            \"3. Practical applications\",\n            \"4. Conclusion\",\n        ]\n        # Return value is passed to @listen(create_outline) steps\n        return self.state.outline\n\n    @listen(create_outline)\n    def write_draft(self, outline: list):\n        # outline == self.state.outline (same value, passed as arg)\n        draft_sections = [f\"## {section}\" for section in outline]\n        self.state.draft = \"\\n\\n\".join(draft_sections)\n        self.state.word_count = len(self.state.draft.split())\n\n    @listen(write_draft)\n    def review(self):\n        # Reads state populated by write_draft\n        if self.state.word_count >= 100:\n            self.state.review_passed = True\n            return \"pass\"\n        else:\n            self.state.review_passed = False\n            return \"fail\" "
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Unstructured State (dict-based)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For quick prototyping, skip the Pydantic model and use the default unstructured state \u2014 a plain dict accessible via "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "self.state",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". This sacrifices type safety but removes boilerplate."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from crewai.flow.flow import Flow, listen, start\n\n# No type parameter \u2014 uses default unstructured state (dict)\nclass QuickFlow(Flow):\n\n    @start()\n    def step_one(self):\n        self.state[\"result\"] = \"hello\"\n        return self.state[\"result\"]\n\n    @listen(step_one)\n    def step_two(self, msg: str):\n        self.state[\"final\"] = msg.upper()\n\nflow = QuickFlow()\nflow.kickoff()\nprint(flow.state)  # {'result': 'hello', 'final': 'HELLO'}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Use typed state (Pydantic) in production. Type errors in an unstructured state are discovered at runtime, not at development time. IDE autocomplete also only works with typed state."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "State Field Validation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pydantic validators run on every field write. Use them to enforce invariants \u2014 for example, ensure word counts stay non-negative or status values are within an allowed set."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from pydantic import BaseModel, field_validator\nfrom typing import Literal\n\nclass ArticleState(BaseModel):\n    title: str = \"\"\n    body: str = \"\"\n    word_count: int = 0\n    status: Literal[\"draft\", \"review\", \"published\"] = \"draft\"\n\n    @field_validator(\"word_count\")\n    @classmethod\n    def word_count_non_negative(cls, v):\n        if v < 0:\n            raise ValueError(\"word_count cannot be negative\")\n        return v\n\n# In a flow step:\n# self.state.word_count = -5  \u2192 raises ValidationError immediately\n# self.state.status = \"deleted\"  \u2192 raises ValidationError (not in Literal)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Nested State Models"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "State models can contain nested Pydantic models for complex structured data."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from pydantic import BaseModel\nfrom typing import List, Optional\n\nclass Source(BaseModel):\n    url: str\n    title: str\n    reliability: float = 1.0\n\nclass ResearchState(BaseModel):\n    topic: str = \"\"\n    sources: List[Source] = []\n    summary: str = \"\"\n\nclass ResearchFlow(Flow[ResearchState]):\n\n    @start()\n    def gather_sources(self):\n        self.state.sources = [\n            Source(url=\"https://arxiv.org/...\", title=\"Quantum Error Correction\", reliability=0.95),\n            Source(url=\"https://nature.com/...\", title=\"Topological Qubits\", reliability=0.99),\n        ]\n\n    @listen(gather_sources)\n    def summarise(self):\n        high_quality = [s for s in self.state.sources if s.reliability >= 0.95]\n        self.state.summary = f\"Found {len(high_quality)} high-reliability sources.\"\n        return self.state.summary"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Accessing State After the Flow"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "After "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "flow.kickoff()",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " returns, the full state is available on the flow instance. This is the recommended way to read final results rather than parsing the return value."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "flow = ResearchFlow()\nflow.kickoff(inputs={\"topic\": \"fusion energy\"})\n\n# Access any field directly\nprint(flow.state.final_article)\nprint(flow.state.word_count)\nprint(flow.state.review_passed)\n\n# Serialise the final state to JSON\nimport json\nstate_json = flow.state.model_dump_json(indent=2)\nprint(state_json)\n\n# Save to file for later inspection\nwith open(\"flow_output.json\", \"w\") as f:\n    f.write(state_json)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "State in Persisted (Resumable) Flows"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "flow_id",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is provided to "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "kickoff()",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", CrewAI serialises the state to disk after every step. If the flow crashes, re-running with the same "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "flow_id",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " restores the last saved state and skips already-completed steps."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import uuid\n\nflow_id = str(uuid.uuid4())\nprint(f\"Flow ID: {flow_id}\")  # save this externally\n\nflow = ResearchFlow()\ntry:\n    result = flow.kickoff(\n        inputs={\"topic\": \"quantum computing\"},\n        flow_id=flow_id,\n    )\nexcept Exception as e:\n    print(f\"Flow failed at step: {e}\")\n    print(\"Run again with the same flow_id to resume\")\n\n# On the next run (after fixing the failure):\nflow2 = ResearchFlow()\nresult = flow2.kickoff(\n    inputs={\"topic\": \"quantum computing\"},\n    flow_id=flow_id,  # picks up from where it left off\n)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Persisted state is stored in "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "~/.crewai/flows/<flow_id>.json",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". Override the directory via the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "CREWAI_STORAGE_DIR",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " environment variable."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Passing State to Embedded Crews"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Since steps are plain Python, you can pass any state field as an input to a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Crew.kickoff()",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " call and write the result back to state."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "class DocumentFlow(Flow[ResearchState]):\n\n    @start()\n    def research(self):\n        # Crew reads topic from inputs; result goes into state\n        result = research_crew.kickoff(inputs={\n            \"topic\": self.state.topic,\n            \"audience\": self.state.audience,\n        })\n        self.state.summary = result.raw\n\n    @listen(research)\n    def write(self):\n        result = writing_crew.kickoff(inputs={\n            \"summary\": self.state.summary,\n            \"audience\": self.state.audience,\n        })\n        self.state.final_article = result.raw\n        return self.state.final_article"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "State vs. Return Values \u2014 When to Use Each"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The two data-passing mechanisms serve different roles and are not interchangeable:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Return value: tightly coupled step-to-step, one downstream consumer\nclass SingleConsumerFlow(Flow[ResearchState]):\n\n    @start()\n    def fetch(self):\n        data = \"raw API data\"\n        return data  # passed directly to the one listener\n\n    @listen(fetch)\n    def parse(self, raw_data: str):\n        # raw_data is the return value of fetch()\n        self.state.summary = raw_data.upper()\n\n# State: shared data needed by multiple downstream steps\nclass MultiConsumerFlow(Flow[ResearchState]):\n\n    @start()\n    def fetch(self):\n        self.state.raw_data = \"raw API data\"  # available to ALL downstream steps\n\n    @listen(fetch)\n    def summarise(self):\n        self.state.summary = self.state.raw_data[:100]\n\n    @listen(fetch)\n    def index(self):\n        self.state.word_count = len(self.state.raw_data.split())\n\n    # Both summarise and index can access self.state.raw_data"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Rule of thumb: if only one downstream step needs the value, return it. If two or more downstream steps need it, write it to state."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Computed State Properties"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pydantic models support "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "@property",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "@computed_field",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " for derived values that are not stored but computed on demand."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from pydantic import BaseModel, computed_field\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass ArticleState(BaseModel):\n    sections: List[str] = []\n    title: str = \"\"\n\n    @computed_field\n    @property\n    def section_count(self) -> int:\n        return len(self.sections)\n\n    @computed_field\n    @property\n    def is_complete(self) -> bool:\n        return bool(self.title and self.sections)\n\nclass ArticleFlow(Flow[ArticleState]):\n\n    @start()\n    def build(self):\n        self.state.title = \"My Article\"\n        self.state.sections = [\"Intro\", \"Body\", \"Conclusion\"]\n        # section_count and is_complete are available without explicit writes\n        print(self.state.section_count)  # 3\n        print(self.state.is_complete)    # True"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "State Isolation Between Runs"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Each "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "flow.kickoff()",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " call creates a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "fresh state instance",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " from defaults. States do not bleed between runs unless you explicitly pass a pre-populated state."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "flow = ResearchFlow()\n\n# Run 1\nflow.kickoff(inputs={\"topic\": \"quantum computing\"})\nprint(flow.state.topic)  # \"quantum computing\"\n\n# Run 2 \u2014 fresh state, topic resets to \"\"\nflow.kickoff(inputs={\"topic\": \"fusion energy\"})\nprint(flow.state.topic)  # \"fusion energy\"\n\n# To inspect state after a run, save it before kicking off again\nimport copy\nstate_after_run1 = copy.deepcopy(flow.state) "
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Sharing State Across Nested Crews with a State Bridge"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When a Crew is embedded in a flow step, it does not directly access "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "self.state",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
